00:01:30.070 --> 00:01:34.700
today, in religious terms, is
Silicon Valley, not the Middle

00:01:34.700 --> 00:01:38.630
East, not Syria, or Afghanistan,
or Israel, or Jerusalem,

00:01:38.630 --> 00:01:40.320
but Silicon Valley.

00:01:40.320 --> 00:01:44.230
This is where the new religions
that will take over the world

00:01:44.230 --> 00:01:46.220
are being formulated.

00:01:46.220 --> 00:01:50.351
And this will also be the topic
of my talk for the next hour

00:01:50.351 --> 00:01:54.750
or so, about the new
religions of the 21st century.

00:01:54.750 --> 00:01:58.060
But in order to understand
the future of religion

00:01:58.060 --> 00:02:02.880
we first have to say a few words
about its past and its present.

00:02:02.880 --> 00:02:07.660
And I would like to
start with describing

00:02:07.660 --> 00:02:11.940
what is the main religion,
or ideology, worldview

00:02:11.940 --> 00:02:15.950
of the world today in the
middle of the second decade

00:02:15.950 --> 00:02:18.450
of the 21st century.

00:02:18.450 --> 00:02:22.790
And I think we can say that the
dominant ideology of the world

00:02:22.790 --> 00:02:28.850
at present is liberal humanism,
or in short, liberalism.

00:02:28.850 --> 00:02:31.670
Liberalism is a
worldview, an ideology,

00:02:31.670 --> 00:02:36.770
that thinks that a source of
all authority and all meaning

00:02:36.770 --> 00:02:40.080
in the universe is
the individual human,

00:02:40.080 --> 00:02:44.130
the individual of the
specie Homo sapiens.

00:02:44.130 --> 00:02:48.820
Liberalism has
several core ideas.

00:02:48.820 --> 00:02:53.340
First of all, it believes
in the individual.

00:02:53.340 --> 00:02:59.240
It thinks that every Homo
sapien is an individual,

00:02:59.240 --> 00:03:02.290
which literally means
it cannot be divided.

00:03:02.290 --> 00:03:04.450
The meaning of the
term "individual"

00:03:04.450 --> 00:03:06.475
is that you cannot divide it.

00:03:06.475 --> 00:03:09.350
The idea is, yes, of course,
you can divide the human body

00:03:09.350 --> 00:03:13.950
or the human brain, but within
each individual there is kind

00:03:13.950 --> 00:03:19.870
of a seed of light, a spark
that cannot be divided further.

00:03:19.870 --> 00:03:23.550
Within each of us there
is this inner voice

00:03:23.550 --> 00:03:26.940
and this inner voice in
each and every one of us

00:03:26.940 --> 00:03:30.390
is the source of all the
meaning and all the authority

00:03:30.390 --> 00:03:31.800
in the world.

00:03:31.800 --> 00:03:34.840
Whenever we face a
difficult question,

00:03:34.840 --> 00:03:37.450
a difficult dilemma,
choice in life

00:03:37.450 --> 00:03:41.650
as individuals, or as
collectives, liberalism tells

00:03:41.650 --> 00:03:45.470
us, listen to yourself,
connect to yourself.

00:03:45.470 --> 00:03:49.230
Try to hear this inner
voice within yourself

00:03:49.230 --> 00:03:52.120
and it will tell you what to do.

00:03:52.120 --> 00:03:55.480
And listen to that,
not to anything else.

00:03:55.480 --> 00:04:00.310
The second main idea or
hypothesis of liberalism

00:04:00.310 --> 00:04:03.990
is that this inner
voice within ourselves

00:04:03.990 --> 00:04:08.200
comes out of a space
of complete freedom.

00:04:08.200 --> 00:04:11.600
Yes, there are influences,
constraints from outside,

00:04:11.600 --> 00:04:16.100
physical, social, biological,
but if we go deep enough

00:04:16.100 --> 00:04:19.010
within ourselves, we
will come, eventually,

00:04:19.010 --> 00:04:21.480
to a space of complete freedom.

00:04:21.480 --> 00:04:26.860
And from the space we need to
make our big decisions in life.

00:04:26.860 --> 00:04:31.090
Thirdly, based on these two
ideas or two assumptions,

00:04:31.090 --> 00:04:36.980
liberalism assumes that only
I can really know myself.

00:04:36.980 --> 00:04:41.920
Nobody else, no outside person,
no outside system can really

00:04:41.920 --> 00:04:46.140
know who I am because,
again, who I am really

00:04:46.140 --> 00:04:50.620
is this inner voice which
enjoys complete freedom.

00:04:50.620 --> 00:04:54.230
So I'm inaccessible
from outside.

00:04:54.230 --> 00:04:58.360
Based on these ideas the
main value of liberalism,

00:04:58.360 --> 00:05:02.150
which gives it its name,
is liberty, freedom.

00:05:02.150 --> 00:05:05.330
We need to preserve the
freedom of the individual

00:05:05.330 --> 00:05:08.350
to think, to feel,
and to act according

00:05:08.350 --> 00:05:11.510
to what he or she thinks and
feels because, again, this

00:05:11.510 --> 00:05:15.170
is the supreme and source
of authority and meaning

00:05:15.170 --> 00:05:16.400
in the world.

00:05:16.400 --> 00:05:21.750
Now all this may sound very
abstract and very theoretical.

00:05:21.750 --> 00:05:25.020
So I would like to give
a few concrete examples

00:05:25.020 --> 00:05:28.140
of what liberalism
means in practice

00:05:28.140 --> 00:05:33.340
to our lives as individuals
and as collectives.

00:05:33.340 --> 00:05:36.940
If you think about the
field of politics, so

00:05:36.940 --> 00:05:38.390
what is liberal politics?

00:05:38.390 --> 00:05:41.640
What is liberalism translated
into political terms?

00:05:41.640 --> 00:05:45.390
You get a democracy with
elections and so forth.

00:05:45.390 --> 00:05:50.410
If we want to know who should
rule this country, what kind

00:05:50.410 --> 00:05:54.240
of economic policies to adopt,
what kind of foreign policy

00:05:54.240 --> 00:05:57.110
to adopt, to make
war or to make peace,

00:05:57.110 --> 00:06:00.950
who should we turn to
in order to get answers?

00:06:00.950 --> 00:06:05.370
We should turn to the inner
voices of each individual.

00:06:05.370 --> 00:06:08.630
So we have elections and
on election day everybody

00:06:08.630 --> 00:06:12.530
goes by himself or by herself.

00:06:12.530 --> 00:06:15.870
And at least theoretically
tries to connect,

00:06:15.870 --> 00:06:18.310
I try to connect to
myself to listen,

00:06:18.310 --> 00:06:20.410
what are my deepest feelings?

00:06:20.410 --> 00:06:24.090
What's are my deepest personal
thoughts about this issue?

00:06:24.090 --> 00:06:26.110
And I vote accordingly.

00:06:26.110 --> 00:06:28.350
And this is how
we know who should

00:06:28.350 --> 00:06:31.470
rule the country, whether
to make peace or war,

00:06:31.470 --> 00:06:32.970
and so forth.

00:06:32.970 --> 00:06:35.320
So this is liberal
politics, which

00:06:35.320 --> 00:06:38.170
argues that the
voter knows best.

00:06:38.170 --> 00:06:43.930
There is no source of authority
higher than the voter.

00:06:43.930 --> 00:06:48.190
You get the same ideas
also in the economic field.

00:06:48.190 --> 00:06:50.360
What is liberal economics?

00:06:50.360 --> 00:06:54.020
Liberal economics is the view
that the customer is always

00:06:54.020 --> 00:06:55.050
right.

00:06:55.050 --> 00:06:58.740
There is no higher
authority than the authority

00:06:58.740 --> 00:07:00.900
of the individual customer.

00:07:00.900 --> 00:07:03.830
How do we know if a
product is a good product?

00:07:03.830 --> 00:07:05.360
If the customers buy it.

00:07:05.360 --> 00:07:07.130
There is no other method.

00:07:07.130 --> 00:07:09.240
There is no higher
authority that

00:07:09.240 --> 00:07:12.200
can say, yes, they didn't
buy it, but it's still good.

00:07:12.200 --> 00:07:14.460
Let's say we are planning a car.

00:07:14.460 --> 00:07:17.280
And we are organizing
a committee

00:07:17.280 --> 00:07:19.960
of the wisest people
on the planet.

00:07:19.960 --> 00:07:23.530
We take Nobel laureates
in physics, and chemistry,

00:07:23.530 --> 00:07:25.850
and literature, and
peace, and whatever

00:07:25.850 --> 00:07:28.530
and they come together
for five years

00:07:28.530 --> 00:07:30.460
with a lot of money,
a lot of helpers.

00:07:30.460 --> 00:07:33.600
And they design the perfect car.

00:07:33.600 --> 00:07:36.090
And after five years
you start producing

00:07:36.090 --> 00:07:40.780
this perfect car, engineered,
invented by the wisest people

00:07:40.780 --> 00:07:41.780
on the planet.

00:07:41.780 --> 00:07:45.470
And it goes on sale
and nobody buys it,

00:07:45.470 --> 00:07:47.090
or very few people buy it.

00:07:47.090 --> 00:07:51.500
It means that this car is
not a good car according

00:07:51.500 --> 00:07:53.390
to the tenets of
liberal economics.

00:07:53.390 --> 00:07:55.457
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:07:55.457 --> 00:07:56.540
YUVAL HARARI: Oh, perhaps.

00:07:56.540 --> 00:07:59.010
But eventually you cannot
blame the customer.

00:07:59.010 --> 00:08:02.810
Oh, we produce a perfect
car and we [? build ?]

00:08:02.810 --> 00:08:07.900
a perfect PR campaign, but the
customers, they are stupid.

00:08:07.900 --> 00:08:10.560
They don't understand
what is good for them.

00:08:10.560 --> 00:08:13.050
This works in
communism, for example.

00:08:13.050 --> 00:08:15.170
This is the idea of communism.

00:08:15.170 --> 00:08:18.420
You have really wise
people sitting in Moscow.

00:08:18.420 --> 00:08:21.350
They plan the car, which
they think is best.

00:08:21.350 --> 00:08:25.040
And everybody, at least if they
are fortunate, gets this car.

00:08:25.040 --> 00:08:27.630
And if they don't like
it, it's their problem.

00:08:27.630 --> 00:08:29.200
But not in liberal economics.

00:08:29.200 --> 00:08:32.490
In liberal economics the
highest authority in economics

00:08:32.490 --> 00:08:35.350
is the customer.

00:08:35.350 --> 00:08:40.110
You have the same ideas in the
fields of art and aesthetics.

00:08:40.110 --> 00:08:43.350
Many times in history many
periods, many cultures, people

00:08:43.350 --> 00:08:46.570
had ideas, what is art
and what is beauty?

00:08:46.570 --> 00:08:51.510
And they thought that there
are some objective definitions,

00:08:51.510 --> 00:08:55.520
objective yardsticks to
determine whether something

00:08:55.520 --> 00:08:58.580
is art and whether
something is good art.

00:08:58.580 --> 00:09:01.720
And then comes along liberal
art and liberal aesthetics

00:09:01.720 --> 00:09:04.140
in the 19th, 20th century.

00:09:04.140 --> 00:09:07.580
And just as in politics
the voter knows best.

00:09:07.580 --> 00:09:11.180
And in economics the
customer is always right.

00:09:11.180 --> 00:09:15.350
So in liberal art, also,
the customer or the viewer,

00:09:15.350 --> 00:09:18.440
he is or she is the
highest authority.

00:09:18.440 --> 00:09:23.700
According to liberal art, beauty
is in the eyes of the beholder,

00:09:23.700 --> 00:09:27.580
in the feelings of the
person watching or seeing

00:09:27.580 --> 00:09:32.540
the painting, the architecture,
the play, whatever it is.

00:09:32.540 --> 00:09:36.470
In 1917, in a very,
very famous gesture

00:09:36.470 --> 00:09:40.690
Marcel Duchamp
took a urinal, said

00:09:40.690 --> 00:09:43.950
this art, called it
"Fountain," signed

00:09:43.950 --> 00:09:49.390
his name, Marcel Duchamp,
put it in a museum in Paris,

00:09:49.390 --> 00:09:50.810
said this is art.

00:09:50.810 --> 00:09:52.140
This is beautiful.

00:09:52.140 --> 00:09:55.430
And ever since then in
every introductory course

00:09:55.430 --> 00:09:57.910
to art, to art
history in university

00:09:57.910 --> 00:10:01.500
they bring this image
and the argument starts.

00:10:01.500 --> 00:10:02.180
Is it art?

00:10:02.180 --> 00:10:03.090
No, it's not art.

00:10:03.090 --> 00:10:04.510
Who determines what is art?

00:10:04.510 --> 00:10:05.220
Is it beautiful?

00:10:05.220 --> 00:10:06.200
It's not beautiful.

00:10:06.200 --> 00:10:09.290
And eventually, if
you are liberals,

00:10:09.290 --> 00:10:12.020
you will reach the
conclusion that art

00:10:12.020 --> 00:10:15.590
is whatever I define
to be art and beauty

00:10:15.590 --> 00:10:16.950
is in the eyes of the beholder.

00:10:16.950 --> 00:10:19.120
Whatever I think is
beautiful, it's beautiful.

00:10:19.120 --> 00:10:21.870
And nobody out there
can come to me and say,

00:10:21.870 --> 00:10:24.150
you think it's
beautiful, but it's not.

00:10:24.150 --> 00:10:26.180
There is some higher authority.

00:10:26.180 --> 00:10:28.470
If you think that
this is beautiful art

00:10:28.470 --> 00:10:30.920
and you're willing to pay
millions of dollars for it,

00:10:30.920 --> 00:10:32.720
and it costs millions
of dollars today,

00:10:32.720 --> 00:10:35.330
this fountain, then it's art.

00:10:38.230 --> 00:10:42.220
The same idea is also applied
to the field of ethics.

00:10:42.220 --> 00:10:45.840
How do you know if an
action is good or evil?

00:10:45.840 --> 00:10:48.240
If it's ethical or unethical?

00:10:48.240 --> 00:10:50.340
Well, suppose I live
in the Middle Ages.

00:10:50.340 --> 00:10:52.640
And I fall in love
with another guy.

00:10:52.640 --> 00:10:55.580
And I go to the priest and
tell him in confession this

00:10:55.580 --> 00:10:56.880
and this happened.

00:10:56.880 --> 00:11:00.450
So the priest will say, this is
very evil, what you have done.

00:11:00.450 --> 00:11:01.890
You will go to hell for this.

00:11:01.890 --> 00:11:02.660
Why?

00:11:02.660 --> 00:11:06.010
Because God thinks it's
evil, because scriptures

00:11:06.010 --> 00:11:09.760
say it's evil, because I,
the priest, say this is evil.

00:11:09.760 --> 00:11:13.210
And then I say to the priest,
but I feel very good about it.

00:11:13.210 --> 00:11:16.150
So the priest would say, but
we don't care what you feel.

00:11:16.150 --> 00:11:17.980
Your feelings are unimportant.

00:11:17.980 --> 00:11:22.370
You don't determine what is
good or evil by what you feel.

00:11:22.370 --> 00:11:26.200
Then came liberalism in
the modern age and said no.

00:11:26.200 --> 00:11:29.410
The highest authority
in the field of ethics

00:11:29.410 --> 00:11:31.700
is also the feelings
of individuals.

00:11:31.700 --> 00:11:33.490
There's nothing beyond that.

00:11:33.490 --> 00:11:35.780
If it feels good, do it.

00:11:35.780 --> 00:11:39.360
If you feel good about it, if
everybody feels good about it,

00:11:39.360 --> 00:11:42.020
then there is absolutely
no reason in the world

00:11:42.020 --> 00:11:44.990
why it should be evil or bad.

00:11:44.990 --> 00:11:46.700
Now, there are, of
course, problems.

00:11:46.700 --> 00:11:51.090
What happens if a
particular action causes

00:11:51.090 --> 00:11:54.550
some people to feel good and
other people to feel bad?

00:11:54.550 --> 00:11:58.980
This is when you have arguments
within liberal ethics.

00:11:58.980 --> 00:12:02.510
Say, for example, an
extramarital affair.

00:12:02.510 --> 00:12:04.800
I have an affair
outside of marriage.

00:12:04.800 --> 00:12:08.370
I feel very good about it,
but if my spouse finds out

00:12:08.370 --> 00:12:09.820
he will feel bad about it.

00:12:09.820 --> 00:12:12.160
And probably I will
also feel bad about it.

00:12:12.160 --> 00:12:15.530
And if we, say, we divorce as
a result and we have children,

00:12:15.530 --> 00:12:17.300
they will feel bad about it.

00:12:17.300 --> 00:12:20.185
So what is more important,
my good feelings

00:12:20.185 --> 00:12:23.680
at a particular time, or the
bad feelings of my spouse,

00:12:23.680 --> 00:12:25.380
or my children?

00:12:25.380 --> 00:12:28.440
Different people have different
views on this question,

00:12:28.440 --> 00:12:32.030
but as long as they are
liberal, the argument

00:12:32.030 --> 00:12:35.200
will be done in
terms of feelings.

00:12:35.200 --> 00:12:38.940
The question will be, what
feeling is more important?

00:12:38.940 --> 00:12:42.860
Even very religious people
today understand this.

00:12:42.860 --> 00:12:46.700
And if you think about the
terrorist attacks in France

00:12:46.700 --> 00:12:49.660
on the Charlie Hebdo,
after the attack

00:12:49.660 --> 00:12:53.470
all kinds of organizations,
Muslim organizations and even

00:12:53.470 --> 00:12:56.110
non-Muslim organizations
began to say things

00:12:56.110 --> 00:12:59.460
like, but look,
this newspaper, it

00:12:59.460 --> 00:13:02.200
was not doing something
very wholesome

00:13:02.200 --> 00:13:05.940
because it was causing
millions of devout Muslims

00:13:05.940 --> 00:13:08.380
around the world to feel bad.

00:13:08.380 --> 00:13:12.170
It didn't take into
account their feelings.

00:13:12.170 --> 00:13:14.700
Now it's very interesting
that they use this argument

00:13:14.700 --> 00:13:17.110
because even those
who try to say it's

00:13:17.110 --> 00:13:21.780
not good to draw a caricature
of the prophet Mohammad,

00:13:21.780 --> 00:13:25.260
they don't say it's not good
because Allah forbade it,

00:13:25.260 --> 00:13:28.670
or because it's wrong
according to the Quran.

00:13:28.670 --> 00:13:31.350
They say it's not
good because it

00:13:31.350 --> 00:13:34.160
hurts the feelings of people.

00:13:34.160 --> 00:13:38.200
So even those
arguments are praised

00:13:38.200 --> 00:13:39.965
in liberal terms of feelings.

00:13:42.490 --> 00:13:45.040
And finally, just to
give a last example

00:13:45.040 --> 00:13:47.920
from the field of education.

00:13:47.920 --> 00:13:50.010
What is liberal education?

00:13:50.010 --> 00:13:53.270
The main idea of
liberal education

00:13:53.270 --> 00:13:57.530
is that the student or the
pupil is the highest authority,

00:13:57.530 --> 00:13:59.615
not the teacher,
not the professor.

00:13:59.615 --> 00:14:03.000
In liberal education
the main thing

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:06.350
you try to teach your
pupils or your students

00:14:06.350 --> 00:14:09.240
is to think for themselves.

00:14:09.240 --> 00:14:10.860
They are the highest authority.

00:14:10.860 --> 00:14:15.790
You go from kindergarten
to the university

00:14:15.790 --> 00:14:18.290
and you ask the teacher,
you ask the professor,

00:14:18.290 --> 00:14:20.510
what are you trying to teach?

00:14:20.510 --> 00:14:23.090
And he or she will
say, well, I try

00:14:23.090 --> 00:14:26.560
to teach history, or
mathematics, or physics,

00:14:26.560 --> 00:14:29.610
but above all I try
to teach my students

00:14:29.610 --> 00:14:31.350
to think for themselves.

00:14:31.350 --> 00:14:33.730
This is the most
important thing.

00:14:33.730 --> 00:14:37.460
If he or she are liberal
educators it doesn't always

00:14:37.460 --> 00:14:41.530
work, of course, not all
the universities or schools

00:14:41.530 --> 00:14:45.690
manage to do it, but this is
the general ideal accepted

00:14:45.690 --> 00:14:48.610
by all liberal
institutions of education.

00:14:52.120 --> 00:14:56.110
Now when we look at the
world of today in 2015

00:14:56.110 --> 00:15:00.260
we can say that the
liberal package dominates

00:15:00.260 --> 00:15:01.940
most of the world.

00:15:01.940 --> 00:15:05.670
This liberal package
contains human rights,

00:15:05.670 --> 00:15:09.010
which are these walls,
defenses established

00:15:09.010 --> 00:15:13.080
to protect the inner
freedom of each individual.

00:15:13.080 --> 00:15:14.710
This is the human rights.

00:15:14.710 --> 00:15:18.360
This package contains
belief in individualism,

00:15:18.360 --> 00:15:22.130
in liberal democracy,
in free market economy.

00:15:22.130 --> 00:15:25.350
And I think we can say
that not everybody accepts

00:15:25.350 --> 00:15:27.620
this particular
package, but it is

00:15:27.620 --> 00:15:31.600
the dominant ideological
package of the world today.

00:15:31.600 --> 00:15:35.320
And there is very little
viable alternatives,

00:15:35.320 --> 00:15:41.010
or real alternatives to
this package at present.

00:15:41.010 --> 00:15:45.860
Over the last few years, we have
seen a lot of social protests

00:15:45.860 --> 00:15:47.640
in different places
in the world,

00:15:47.640 --> 00:15:50.530
but the vast majority
of the protests

00:15:50.530 --> 00:15:53.800
were done in the name
of the liberal values,

00:15:53.800 --> 00:15:55.440
not against them.

00:15:55.440 --> 00:15:58.140
People are coming to the
governments and saying,

00:15:58.140 --> 00:16:01.130
you don't live up to
the liberal ideas.

00:16:01.130 --> 00:16:05.400
We want the politics
to be more democratic.

00:16:05.400 --> 00:16:10.400
We want economics, the
economy, to be more free.

00:16:10.400 --> 00:16:12.640
The vast majority
of social protests

00:16:12.640 --> 00:16:15.520
did not have any
alternative to this package.

00:16:15.520 --> 00:16:19.570
They simply wanted it
to be implemented better

00:16:19.570 --> 00:16:22.330
than it is being
implemented today.

00:16:22.330 --> 00:16:26.100
Another potential source
for an alternative

00:16:26.100 --> 00:16:28.340
which more and more
people speak about

00:16:28.340 --> 00:16:34.720
is China, the rising
superpower of the 21st century.

00:16:34.720 --> 00:16:40.280
However, even though China is
definitely an economic giant,

00:16:40.280 --> 00:16:44.660
it is still an
ideological dwarf.

00:16:44.660 --> 00:16:48.730
In terms of ideology or
religion China has very little

00:16:48.730 --> 00:16:50.890
to offer the world,
at least at present.

00:16:50.890 --> 00:16:56.840
In theory and officially, it
is still a communist country,

00:16:56.840 --> 00:17:00.710
but it is very far from
being communist in practice.

00:17:00.710 --> 00:17:03.920
And it has no alternative
idea to either

00:17:03.920 --> 00:17:07.190
its official communism
or to the liberal package

00:17:07.190 --> 00:17:12.060
of how else to run human
society in terms of values.

00:17:12.060 --> 00:17:15.510
Maybe in the next decade,
two decades, three decades

00:17:15.510 --> 00:17:18.130
we will see the rise of
a completely new ideology

00:17:18.130 --> 00:17:22.210
in China, but
speaking as of 2015,

00:17:22.210 --> 00:17:25.864
China is extremely good in
business, in making money,

00:17:25.864 --> 00:17:28.680
in making products,
but ideologically it

00:17:28.680 --> 00:17:31.440
seems to be bankrupt.

00:17:31.440 --> 00:17:35.440
The third main alternative
to the liberal package

00:17:35.440 --> 00:17:38.580
is radical Islam, or radical
religions in general,

00:17:38.580 --> 00:17:42.350
but very often we
focus on radical Islam.

00:17:42.350 --> 00:17:45.810
However, even though radical
fundamentalist Islamic

00:17:45.810 --> 00:17:49.200
movements oppose
the liberal package,

00:17:49.200 --> 00:17:54.380
they don't really have
any relevant alternative

00:17:54.380 --> 00:17:56.750
that can be offered
and implemented

00:17:56.750 --> 00:18:00.190
in the 21st century.

00:18:00.190 --> 00:18:05.850
The reason is that most of
their ideas are out of date

00:18:05.850 --> 00:18:09.130
by centuries, by
hundreds of years.

00:18:09.130 --> 00:18:15.490
The 21st century challenges
humankind in new ways.

00:18:15.490 --> 00:18:18.430
We are facing enormous
opportunities,

00:18:18.430 --> 00:18:22.420
enormous new opportunities,
and enormous new dangers

00:18:22.420 --> 00:18:25.510
that we need to confront.

00:18:25.510 --> 00:18:29.330
And radical Islam has very
little relevant things

00:18:29.330 --> 00:18:33.690
to say about these new
challenges and new dangers.

00:18:33.690 --> 00:18:38.050
To give just a few examples,
perhaps the most important

00:18:38.050 --> 00:18:41.500
question in
21st-century economics

00:18:41.500 --> 00:18:45.610
is what do we need people
for in the economy?

00:18:45.610 --> 00:18:48.730
In a situation when it
is likely that computers

00:18:48.730 --> 00:18:53.030
will be able to do more and
more things better and better

00:18:53.030 --> 00:18:56.570
than Homo sapiens, this
becomes a real question

00:18:56.570 --> 00:18:58.740
for the first time in history.

00:18:58.740 --> 00:19:03.670
The most basic economic value
of humans is being put in doubt.

00:19:03.670 --> 00:19:07.020
And nobody really has an
idea how the job market would

00:19:07.020 --> 00:19:09.760
look like in 40
years or 50 years,

00:19:09.760 --> 00:19:12.160
and what humans will
still be necessary for,

00:19:12.160 --> 00:19:13.690
or least most humans.

00:19:13.690 --> 00:19:15.400
What will they do?

00:19:15.400 --> 00:19:19.070
If there is a young man or
woman today, say, 20 years old,

00:19:19.070 --> 00:19:22.720
going to college, and
asking himself or herself

00:19:22.720 --> 00:19:26.900
what should I study
today so that in 30 years

00:19:26.900 --> 00:19:28.840
I will have a good job?

00:19:28.840 --> 00:19:30.570
Nobody knows what
to tell him or her.

00:19:30.570 --> 00:19:31.540
Nobody knows.

00:19:31.540 --> 00:19:34.620
We don't have a clue
how the job market would

00:19:34.620 --> 00:19:37.850
look in 30 or 40 years.

00:19:37.850 --> 00:19:39.530
And again, it's not even clear.

00:19:39.530 --> 00:19:41.810
It's not that there
will be different jobs.

00:19:41.810 --> 00:19:43.460
It's not even clear
that there will

00:19:43.460 --> 00:19:46.770
be any jobs for most humans.

00:19:46.770 --> 00:19:51.070
Another very big
challenge and opportunity

00:19:51.070 --> 00:19:53.370
concerns biotechnology.

00:19:53.370 --> 00:19:56.860
The possibility of extending
human life and human health

00:19:56.860 --> 00:20:00.810
indefinitely, with
80 being the new 40.

00:20:00.810 --> 00:20:06.060
What will this do to
society, to sexual relations,

00:20:06.060 --> 00:20:07.530
to family structures?

00:20:07.530 --> 00:20:10.090
This is very big questions.

00:20:10.090 --> 00:20:12.670
Another very big
question, which emanates

00:20:12.670 --> 00:20:15.910
from this field of
biotechnology is the possibility

00:20:15.910 --> 00:20:20.460
of, for the first time in
history, real biological gaps

00:20:20.460 --> 00:20:23.170
opening between the
rich and the poor.

00:20:23.170 --> 00:20:25.270
Previously in history
there were always

00:20:25.270 --> 00:20:28.550
gaps between rich and
poor, but these gaps

00:20:28.550 --> 00:20:32.820
were social, economic,
legal, not biological.

00:20:32.820 --> 00:20:35.840
There was no real
biological difference

00:20:35.840 --> 00:20:38.170
between the king
and the peasant.

00:20:38.170 --> 00:20:41.700
They had the same basic
physical, cognitive,

00:20:41.700 --> 00:20:43.490
and emotional abilities.

00:20:43.490 --> 00:20:45.870
Now with the advent
of biotechnology

00:20:45.870 --> 00:20:48.400
we are facing a possibility,
it's not a prophecy,

00:20:48.400 --> 00:20:51.110
it's not certain, but
there is a possibility

00:20:51.110 --> 00:20:55.640
of real biological gaps opening
and Homo sapiens splitting

00:20:55.640 --> 00:20:58.610
into different biological
castes, or even

00:20:58.610 --> 00:21:00.650
different species.

00:21:00.650 --> 00:21:02.720
These are the kinds
of problems that we

00:21:02.720 --> 00:21:05.320
need to confront in
the 21st century.

00:21:05.320 --> 00:21:08.740
And the problem of radical
Islam and radical Christianity,

00:21:08.740 --> 00:21:11.030
Judaism, and so
forth, is that they

00:21:11.030 --> 00:21:15.300
have nothing relevant to
say about these questions.

00:21:15.300 --> 00:21:18.070
They have no answers
to these questions

00:21:18.070 --> 00:21:21.240
because they don't even
understand the questions.

00:21:21.240 --> 00:21:26.080
If you read even very wise books
written thousands of years ago,

00:21:26.080 --> 00:21:30.890
the people who wrote these books
knew nothing about genetics,

00:21:30.890 --> 00:21:34.270
knew nothing about
nanotechnology, or computers.

00:21:34.270 --> 00:21:38.340
So how can you expect to get
answers to these questions

00:21:38.340 --> 00:21:41.000
from people who
didn't know anything

00:21:41.000 --> 00:21:42.650
about the subjects in question?

00:21:45.910 --> 00:21:50.760
Now it's true that if you count
heads, if you count people

00:21:50.760 --> 00:21:53.085
there are many more people
today on the planet that

00:21:53.085 --> 00:21:56.180
are interested in
God and scriptures

00:21:56.180 --> 00:21:58.580
than in nanotechnology
or genetics,

00:21:58.580 --> 00:22:01.690
or who understand
these subjects.

00:22:01.690 --> 00:22:05.100
But history is not
made by numbers.

00:22:05.100 --> 00:22:07.470
It's not that you
need a lot of people

00:22:07.470 --> 00:22:09.870
to make historical changes.

00:22:09.870 --> 00:22:11.810
Very often historical
changes are

00:22:11.810 --> 00:22:15.170
made by relatively
few numbers of people.

00:22:15.170 --> 00:22:20.200
If we go back to the last big
technological and economic

00:22:20.200 --> 00:22:23.940
revolution that swept
the world, the Industrial

00:22:23.940 --> 00:22:30.890
Revolution of the 19th century,
it was done by very few people.

00:22:30.890 --> 00:22:34.330
Most people in the 19th
century knew far more

00:22:34.330 --> 00:22:38.070
and were interested far more
in the Bible and the Quran

00:22:38.070 --> 00:22:42.380
than in steam engines, or
railroads, or coal mines.

00:22:42.380 --> 00:22:46.260
The same thing we see today, we
saw also in the 19th century.

00:22:46.260 --> 00:22:51.320
It was also full of religious
fundamentalist movements.

00:22:51.320 --> 00:22:54.390
For example, in the Islamic
world, you had in Sudan,

00:22:54.390 --> 00:22:57.040
the Mahdi in the late
19th century, which

00:22:57.040 --> 00:22:59.270
established a
religious theocracy.

00:22:59.270 --> 00:23:03.050
And also beheaded people and
fought wars and so forth.

00:23:03.050 --> 00:23:05.890
Caused a lot of [? steel ?]
in Victorian England

00:23:05.890 --> 00:23:08.970
when the followers of
the Mahdi beheaded,

00:23:08.970 --> 00:23:14.590
executed General Charles Gordon,
a famous British commander.

00:23:14.590 --> 00:23:17.790
Nobody almost remembers
the Mahdi today.

00:23:17.790 --> 00:23:21.280
Similarly in India you
had a religious revival

00:23:21.280 --> 00:23:25.780
led by [INAUDIBLE],
whose main idea,

00:23:25.780 --> 00:23:31.910
the main message [INAUDIBLE] had
to India in the 19th century,

00:23:31.910 --> 00:23:36.540
is that all the answers to all
the questions are in the Vedas,

00:23:36.540 --> 00:23:38.670
in the holy scriptures
of Hinduism.

00:23:38.670 --> 00:23:40.360
The Vedas are never wrong.

00:23:40.360 --> 00:23:42.030
All the answers are there.

00:23:42.030 --> 00:23:46.030
If you have any difficulty, open
the Vedas or ask the Brahmans.

00:23:46.030 --> 00:23:49.250
Tens of millions of
people followed him.

00:23:49.250 --> 00:23:52.900
In the Christian world you
also saw such movements.

00:23:52.900 --> 00:23:56.500
Pope Pius IX, the
Catholic pope, he,

00:23:56.500 --> 00:23:58.110
in the middle of
the 19th century

00:23:58.110 --> 00:24:03.910
had this new idea that
the pope is never wrong.

00:24:03.910 --> 00:24:04.710
It is a new idea.

00:24:04.710 --> 00:24:06.780
It's not an idea
for the Middle Ages.

00:24:06.780 --> 00:24:11.210
The Catholic dogma, the Papal
Infallibility, it's called,

00:24:11.210 --> 00:24:14.110
the pope is never
wrong when it comes

00:24:14.110 --> 00:24:17.580
to questions of ethics,
morality, and so forth.

00:24:17.580 --> 00:24:19.910
This is not a medieval dogma.

00:24:19.910 --> 00:24:22.970
It goes back only to the
middle of the 19th century.

00:24:22.970 --> 00:24:28.200
And then millions of people
followed Pope Pius IX.

00:24:28.200 --> 00:24:32.700
In China the biggest
war of the 19th century

00:24:32.700 --> 00:24:36.850
was not the Napoleonic War,
was not the American Civil War.

00:24:36.850 --> 00:24:40.120
By far the biggest war
of the 19th century

00:24:40.120 --> 00:24:44.590
was the Taiping Rebellion,
which started in 1850

00:24:44.590 --> 00:24:49.190
when this person Hong
Xiuquan, he had a vision.

00:24:49.190 --> 00:24:54.420
God revealed himself to
Hong and told Hong a secret

00:24:54.420 --> 00:24:56.890
that Hong was
actually the younger

00:24:56.890 --> 00:24:59.480
brother of Jesus Christ.

00:24:59.480 --> 00:25:03.200
And he had a divine
mission to establish

00:25:03.200 --> 00:25:08.240
the kingdom of Heavenly Peace
on Earth starting with China.

00:25:08.240 --> 00:25:11.170
Millions of people followed
him and they did not

00:25:11.170 --> 00:25:12.590
establish any peace.

00:25:12.590 --> 00:25:15.870
They waged the most terrible
war of the 19th century

00:25:15.870 --> 00:25:18.970
with at least 20 million dead.

00:25:18.970 --> 00:25:22.330
These are the
smallest estimates.

00:25:22.330 --> 00:25:27.020
So you had your full share
of religious fundamentalism

00:25:27.020 --> 00:25:29.300
also back in the 19th century.

00:25:29.300 --> 00:25:32.569
Nobody almost today
remembers these people

00:25:32.569 --> 00:25:33.360
or these movements.

00:25:33.360 --> 00:25:35.660
They did not change the world.

00:25:35.660 --> 00:25:38.620
The Industrial Revolution did.

00:25:38.620 --> 00:25:42.270
Well, these people in Sudan,
or in India, or in China

00:25:42.270 --> 00:25:45.450
were concerned about
scriptures, and God, and heaven,

00:25:45.450 --> 00:25:46.380
and so forth.

00:25:46.380 --> 00:25:49.430
A few engineers and
a few technicians,

00:25:49.430 --> 00:25:52.110
and bankers, and
financiers in Manchester,

00:25:52.110 --> 00:25:54.990
in Liverpool, and Birmingham,
they changed the world.

00:25:54.990 --> 00:25:58.900
They shaped the world
in which we live today.

00:25:58.900 --> 00:26:03.360
Now there was one ideological
or religious movement

00:26:03.360 --> 00:26:05.690
which began in the
19th century which

00:26:05.690 --> 00:26:07.970
did manage to change
the world and which

00:26:07.970 --> 00:26:09.560
is far more important.

00:26:09.560 --> 00:26:12.300
And when we think back
about the 19th century

00:26:12.300 --> 00:26:15.110
and we ask ourselves,
what was the big ideology,

00:26:15.110 --> 00:26:18.820
the big ethical ideas that
came from this period,

00:26:18.820 --> 00:26:22.160
we think not about the
Pope Pius IX, or the Mahdi,

00:26:22.160 --> 00:26:25.310
we think about
socialism and communism.

00:26:25.310 --> 00:26:29.590
In 1800 there were hardly
any socialists or communists,

00:26:29.590 --> 00:26:30.700
very few.

00:26:30.700 --> 00:26:32.820
Even in the middle
of the 19th century,

00:26:32.820 --> 00:26:37.660
there was still a fringe
group of bizarre people

00:26:37.660 --> 00:26:40.310
who have such
thoughts, but there

00:26:40.310 --> 00:26:45.000
was one crucial characteristic
about these bizarre people,

00:26:45.000 --> 00:26:49.300
like Marx and Engels, that
enabled them to really

00:26:49.300 --> 00:26:53.010
change the world and to
create an ideology that

00:26:53.010 --> 00:26:54.940
spread over the entire planet.

00:26:54.940 --> 00:26:58.270
And helped to shape
our life today.

00:26:58.270 --> 00:27:01.150
The crucial thing about
Marx and Engels, and later

00:27:01.150 --> 00:27:03.650
Lenin and Trotsky,
and all these fellows

00:27:03.650 --> 00:27:07.830
is that they did not just
read old books from hundreds

00:27:07.830 --> 00:27:09.750
of centuries previously.

00:27:09.750 --> 00:27:15.060
They studied the technology and
the economy of their own day.

00:27:15.060 --> 00:27:19.540
And they tried to create
a new ideology, which

00:27:19.540 --> 00:27:22.590
will be suited to
the new opportunities

00:27:22.590 --> 00:27:27.150
and challenges of 19th-century
technology and 19th-century

00:27:27.150 --> 00:27:29.270
economics.

00:27:29.270 --> 00:27:32.680
Lenin was once asked in
a very famous occasion,

00:27:32.680 --> 00:27:35.490
Lenin was asked
by his followers,

00:27:35.490 --> 00:27:40.470
please, Vladimir, tell us in
simple language what communism

00:27:40.470 --> 00:27:41.602
is.

00:27:41.602 --> 00:27:43.810
We are not going to read
[? "The Capital," ?] a very,

00:27:43.810 --> 00:27:45.220
very dense book.

00:27:45.220 --> 00:27:48.240
We don't want to hear now
this long philosophical talk.

00:27:48.240 --> 00:27:51.990
In very few words tell
us what communism is.

00:27:51.990 --> 00:27:55.090
And Lenin answers,
communism, communism

00:27:55.090 --> 00:27:59.050
is power to the workers'
councils, the Soviets,

00:27:59.050 --> 00:28:03.170
plus electrification
of the entire country.

00:28:03.170 --> 00:28:07.490
You cannot have communism
without electricity,

00:28:07.490 --> 00:28:11.290
without the steam engine,
without telegraph, radio,

00:28:11.290 --> 00:28:12.470
railroads.

00:28:12.470 --> 00:28:15.450
The Communist system of
production and economics

00:28:15.450 --> 00:28:17.160
demands these things.

00:28:17.160 --> 00:28:19.900
You could not have
established a Communist regime

00:28:19.900 --> 00:28:21.610
in 16th-century Russia.

00:28:21.610 --> 00:28:22.710
Impossible.

00:28:22.710 --> 00:28:25.450
First you must have an
Industrial Revolution.

00:28:25.450 --> 00:28:29.020
Communism and
socialism are custom

00:28:29.020 --> 00:28:33.880
built for the world following
the Industrial Revolution.

00:28:33.880 --> 00:28:36.010
This is why they're
so successful.

00:28:36.010 --> 00:28:40.560
In a way communism and
socialism were the harbingers

00:28:40.560 --> 00:28:42.640
of the new religions
we see today

00:28:42.640 --> 00:28:46.180
in the 21st century in the
sense that they were based

00:28:46.180 --> 00:28:49.120
on technology and
on the economy.

00:28:49.120 --> 00:28:52.860
After thousands of years in
which technology played almost

00:28:52.860 --> 00:28:58.030
no role at all in religious
and ideological thought,

00:28:58.030 --> 00:29:01.870
communism was the first
techno-religion, a religion

00:29:01.870 --> 00:29:05.190
or ideology if you
prefer that promises

00:29:05.190 --> 00:29:09.920
roughly the same things
that were promised

00:29:09.920 --> 00:29:11.710
by the traditional religions.

00:29:11.710 --> 00:29:17.300
It promised peace, prosperity,
paradise, but here on Earth

00:29:17.300 --> 00:29:21.060
with the use of technology,
not in the afterlife

00:29:21.060 --> 00:29:23.650
by the act of some divine power.

00:29:23.650 --> 00:29:26.560
This is the definition
of a techno-religion.

00:29:26.560 --> 00:29:30.080
It promises whatever it
promises here on Earth

00:29:30.080 --> 00:29:32.140
with the help of technology.

00:29:32.140 --> 00:29:36.140
And communism was perhaps
the first to show the way

00:29:36.140 --> 00:29:41.560
and it completely changed our
entire ideological discourse.

00:29:41.560 --> 00:29:45.770
Previously the
main dividing lines

00:29:45.770 --> 00:29:50.600
between people and their beliefs
concerned questions like,

00:29:50.600 --> 00:29:52.640
do we believe in God, what god?

00:29:52.640 --> 00:29:53.700
Do you believe in a soul?

00:29:53.700 --> 00:29:54.750
What kind of soul?

00:29:54.750 --> 00:29:56.260
What happens after death?

00:29:56.260 --> 00:29:59.610
These were the main questions
that divided, say, Christians

00:29:59.610 --> 00:30:03.060
from Muslims and
Shiites from Sunnis.

00:30:03.060 --> 00:30:05.540
After communism
everything changed.

00:30:05.540 --> 00:30:08.630
Now people more and more
began to define themselves

00:30:08.630 --> 00:30:12.540
by how they think about
technology and economics.

00:30:12.540 --> 00:30:15.740
Sounds very strange,
but not very long ago,

00:30:15.740 --> 00:30:18.360
30 years ago,
humankind was almost

00:30:18.360 --> 00:30:23.290
destroyed in a nuclear
war between two camps who

00:30:23.290 --> 00:30:27.050
were divided not in what
they thought about soul,

00:30:27.050 --> 00:30:29.030
or God, or the afterlife.

00:30:29.030 --> 00:30:31.130
The were divided in
what they thought

00:30:31.130 --> 00:30:35.400
about how economic production
should be organized.

00:30:35.400 --> 00:30:38.250
So communism really changed
the rules of the game.

00:30:38.250 --> 00:30:40.880
Even if you don't
accept what Marx said

00:30:40.880 --> 00:30:44.651
you started speaking in
similar terms in the questions

00:30:44.651 --> 00:30:45.275
that you asked.

00:30:48.530 --> 00:30:53.420
And we see indeed that
the traditional religions,

00:30:53.420 --> 00:30:56.540
Hinduism, Islam, Judaism,
Christianity, they

00:30:56.540 --> 00:30:58.330
did not disappear.

00:30:58.330 --> 00:31:00.710
It's not that people
stopped believing in them.

00:31:00.710 --> 00:31:05.830
They just became less and less
relevant, less influential.

00:31:05.830 --> 00:31:08.330
They were transformed
essentially

00:31:08.330 --> 00:31:13.000
from a creative force
into a reactive force.

00:31:13.000 --> 00:31:16.950
In the Middle Ages they
were very creative forces.

00:31:16.950 --> 00:31:20.870
Much of the new technological,
economic, political,

00:31:20.870 --> 00:31:23.730
administrative techniques
of the Middle Ages

00:31:23.730 --> 00:31:26.750
were pioneered by
the Catholic church.

00:31:26.750 --> 00:31:31.530
The best equivalent for Silicon
Valley in the 13th century

00:31:31.530 --> 00:31:33.090
is the Vatican.

00:31:33.090 --> 00:31:36.790
This is where all of the new
ideas about administration,

00:31:36.790 --> 00:31:38.790
about information
processing, this

00:31:38.790 --> 00:31:40.760
is where you went,
to the Vatican.

00:31:40.760 --> 00:31:43.850
The first archives,
libraries, systems

00:31:43.850 --> 00:31:47.430
for archiving information,
cataloging information,

00:31:47.430 --> 00:31:50.130
this is something the
church was best in doing.

00:31:50.130 --> 00:31:52.630
If you are a king
in the 13th century

00:31:52.630 --> 00:31:55.120
and you wanted
somebody who knows

00:31:55.120 --> 00:31:59.760
how to handle information,
to help you run your kingdom,

00:31:59.760 --> 00:32:01.760
you turned to monks.

00:32:01.760 --> 00:32:03.390
You turned to priests.

00:32:03.390 --> 00:32:05.050
They were the experts.

00:32:05.050 --> 00:32:08.660
So back then they were
still very creative forces.

00:32:08.660 --> 00:32:13.030
But in the last 200 years
they became reactive forces.

00:32:13.030 --> 00:32:16.060
They're still there,
but most of what they do

00:32:16.060 --> 00:32:20.320
is react to the changes, to the
inventions, to the discoveries

00:32:20.320 --> 00:32:22.190
that other people make.

00:32:22.190 --> 00:32:25.480
Like somebody invents
the contraceptive pill

00:32:25.480 --> 00:32:29.420
and completely changes
the sexual [? sphere ?].

00:32:29.420 --> 00:32:31.060
And then the pope
and the priests,

00:32:31.060 --> 00:32:33.735
they scratch their head,
what do we do with this?

00:32:33.735 --> 00:32:34.360
What do you do?

00:32:34.360 --> 00:32:35.449
Is it OK?

00:32:35.449 --> 00:32:35.990
Is it not OK?

00:32:35.990 --> 00:32:37.240
They react.

00:32:37.240 --> 00:32:40.070
Similarly somebody
invents the internet.

00:32:40.070 --> 00:32:42.420
And then you have all the
Jewish rabbis also scratching

00:32:42.420 --> 00:32:44.310
their heads, what
do we do with that?

00:32:44.310 --> 00:32:46.180
Is it OK?

00:32:46.180 --> 00:32:48.680
[INAUDIBLE] just use it
like this, like that?

00:32:48.680 --> 00:32:51.000
And it's not only technology.

00:32:51.000 --> 00:32:55.750
Also new ethical ideas, the
20th century is full of them.

00:32:55.750 --> 00:32:58.280
Perhaps the most
important is feminism.

00:32:58.280 --> 00:33:01.880
After thousands of years
of patriarchal society,

00:33:01.880 --> 00:33:04.930
we have the feminist
revolution completely changing

00:33:04.930 --> 00:33:07.740
social structures,
families, and so forth.

00:33:07.740 --> 00:33:10.620
And again, you have all
the rabbis and Ayatollahs,

00:33:10.620 --> 00:33:15.450
and priests, they think, how
do we need to react to that?

00:33:15.450 --> 00:33:19.270
It's not our initiative, but we
have to do something with it.

00:33:19.270 --> 00:33:23.025
So they are reacting in
this way or that way.

00:33:23.025 --> 00:33:26.510
A very good way of
grasping the changing

00:33:26.510 --> 00:33:28.670
place of these
religions in the world

00:33:28.670 --> 00:33:33.040
is to ask yourself
two questions.

00:33:33.040 --> 00:33:38.570
First, ask yourself what is
the most important discovery

00:33:38.570 --> 00:33:41.000
of the 20th century.

00:33:41.000 --> 00:33:43.140
And this is a very
difficult question

00:33:43.140 --> 00:33:45.570
because there is a
lot to choose from.

00:33:45.570 --> 00:33:48.040
Perhaps it's antibiotics.

00:33:48.040 --> 00:33:51.380
Perhaps it gave each one of you
at least 10 years of your life,

00:33:51.380 --> 00:33:53.760
on average, you
owe to antibiotics.

00:33:53.760 --> 00:33:55.520
It's a huge difference.

00:33:55.520 --> 00:33:57.470
Maybe it's nuclear weapons.

00:33:57.470 --> 00:33:59.020
Maybe it's the computer.

00:33:59.020 --> 00:34:02.040
Maybe it's not technology,
but some ethical idea,

00:34:02.040 --> 00:34:03.050
like feminism.

00:34:03.050 --> 00:34:05.650
Perhaps feminism is the
most important discovery

00:34:05.650 --> 00:34:07.500
of the 20th century.

00:34:07.500 --> 00:34:10.070
Difficult question to decide.

00:34:10.070 --> 00:34:12.620
Now ask yourself
a second question.

00:34:12.620 --> 00:34:15.739
What is the most
important discovery made

00:34:15.739 --> 00:34:19.790
in the 20th century by
[? faced ?] religions,

00:34:19.790 --> 00:34:22.730
religions that believe in
God, like Islam, or Hinduism,

00:34:22.730 --> 00:34:24.659
or Judaism.

00:34:24.659 --> 00:34:27.080
Again, it's a very
difficult question

00:34:27.080 --> 00:34:29.929
because you can't
think about anything.

00:34:29.929 --> 00:34:32.590
What did these people
discover in the last 100

00:34:32.590 --> 00:34:34.900
years that changed our lives?

00:34:34.900 --> 00:34:36.820
Yes, they are still
influential in the way

00:34:36.820 --> 00:34:39.929
that they react to the
inventions and discoveries

00:34:39.929 --> 00:34:44.170
of others, but what new
things did they discover?

00:34:44.170 --> 00:34:46.080
I, at least, can't
think about anything

00:34:46.080 --> 00:34:49.270
which you can mention
in the same sentence

00:34:49.270 --> 00:34:52.439
with antibiotics, or
feminism, or nuclear weapons.

00:34:55.510 --> 00:35:00.400
So we see that the
usual challenges

00:35:00.400 --> 00:35:02.550
that we think that
perhaps there are still

00:35:02.550 --> 00:35:06.270
in the world to liberalism
are not really challenges.

00:35:06.270 --> 00:35:09.520
Neither China, nor Radical
Islam, nor the social protests,

00:35:09.520 --> 00:35:13.710
they don't really have
a relevant alternative

00:35:13.710 --> 00:35:15.680
to the liberal package.

00:35:15.680 --> 00:35:20.410
But this does not mean
that liberalism is safe.

00:35:20.410 --> 00:35:21.670
Just the opposite.

00:35:21.670 --> 00:35:24.170
It seems that we
are on the verge

00:35:24.170 --> 00:35:27.170
of the collapse of liberalism.

00:35:27.170 --> 00:35:30.390
And the collapse of
liberalism will not

00:35:30.390 --> 00:35:33.840
happen because of things
that people are doing now

00:35:33.840 --> 00:35:37.640
in Syria, or Iraq, or in
Libya, but because of things

00:35:37.640 --> 00:35:41.160
that people are doing
here in Silicon Valley,

00:35:41.160 --> 00:35:43.345
and in Stanford University,
and in my university,

00:35:43.345 --> 00:35:45.130
and in the Hebrew University.

00:35:45.130 --> 00:35:46.880
What kind of things?

00:35:46.880 --> 00:35:50.310
Well, it starts with
the life sciences.

00:35:50.310 --> 00:35:55.220
The basic problem of liberalism
today in the early 21st century

00:35:55.220 --> 00:36:00.050
is that the life sciences are
telling us that it is nonsense.

00:36:00.050 --> 00:36:04.510
The basic beliefs on which
liberalism are built or perhaps

00:36:04.510 --> 00:36:08.070
sounded sensible in the
18th century, in the era

00:36:08.070 --> 00:36:11.130
of Locke and Rousseau
and these people.

00:36:11.130 --> 00:36:16.220
But there is a huge gap between
what liberalism tells us

00:36:16.220 --> 00:36:19.070
about the world, and
about Homo sapiens,

00:36:19.070 --> 00:36:22.660
and what the life sciences
in the early 21st century

00:36:22.660 --> 00:36:26.100
are telling us
about Homo sapiens.

00:36:26.100 --> 00:36:29.490
Liberalism believes
in individualism

00:36:29.490 --> 00:36:33.380
as we said earlier, that each
one of us is an individual.

00:36:33.380 --> 00:36:38.830
We have this ray of light, this
inner core which is individual.

00:36:38.830 --> 00:36:41.010
This is our real self.

00:36:41.010 --> 00:36:43.670
Well, according to the
life sciences today

00:36:43.670 --> 00:36:45.840
there are no such things.

00:36:45.840 --> 00:36:49.880
All animals, including
humans, are not individuals.

00:36:49.880 --> 00:36:52.150
They don't have souls.

00:36:52.150 --> 00:36:53.640
They don't have any essence.

00:36:53.640 --> 00:36:55.780
They don't have any inner core.

00:36:55.780 --> 00:37:00.660
They are basically a collection
of biochemical algorithms,

00:37:00.660 --> 00:37:03.360
all kinds of
algorithmic systems that

00:37:03.360 --> 00:37:07.070
build the brain, that build
the human beings, the giraffe,

00:37:07.070 --> 00:37:09.210
the elephant, whatever it is.

00:37:09.210 --> 00:37:14.130
And if you peel all the layers,
all the systems that make up

00:37:14.130 --> 00:37:16.812
an animal, an organism
like an onion,

00:37:16.812 --> 00:37:18.270
you peel one layer
after the other,

00:37:18.270 --> 00:37:20.420
one layer after the
other, in the end

00:37:20.420 --> 00:37:24.610
you won't get an inner
core of light, or a soul.

00:37:24.610 --> 00:37:25.930
You will get nothing.

00:37:25.930 --> 00:37:28.950
There is just nothing
left when you take out

00:37:28.950 --> 00:37:32.830
all these different biochemical
algorithms, nothing is left.

00:37:32.830 --> 00:37:35.030
There is no individual.

00:37:35.030 --> 00:37:39.780
Secondly, these
biochemical algorithms

00:37:39.780 --> 00:37:43.380
that make up an
organism are not free.

00:37:43.380 --> 00:37:46.120
There is no such
thing as freedom

00:37:46.120 --> 00:37:48.460
according to the life sciences.

00:37:48.460 --> 00:37:55.190
All systems in nature, including
these biochemical algorithms,

00:37:55.190 --> 00:37:59.910
they work according to just
two possible principles.

00:37:59.910 --> 00:38:05.540
Either they are deterministic
or they are random.

00:38:05.540 --> 00:38:08.020
Perhaps some events
on the quantum level

00:38:08.020 --> 00:38:13.300
insert a certain randomness
into the biochemical processes

00:38:13.300 --> 00:38:15.950
of our brain, of our
nervous system, of our body,

00:38:15.950 --> 00:38:18.560
but that's it.

00:38:18.560 --> 00:38:22.450
The word "freedom"
simply has no meaning

00:38:22.450 --> 00:38:25.610
in the life sciences of today.

00:38:25.610 --> 00:38:30.360
Taking these two ideas together
that an organism, including

00:38:30.360 --> 00:38:32.960
Homo sapiens-- which
is just another animal

00:38:32.960 --> 00:38:34.590
like the chimpanzees,
and giraffes,

00:38:34.590 --> 00:38:37.570
and so forth-- if
an organism is just

00:38:37.570 --> 00:38:41.000
a collection of algorithms,
and these algorithms

00:38:41.000 --> 00:38:44.910
are not free in any
sense, this means

00:38:44.910 --> 00:38:47.910
that at least potentially
an external system,

00:38:47.910 --> 00:38:52.280
an external entity can
understand me perfectly.

00:38:52.280 --> 00:38:55.960
It just needs to understand
all the algorithms that

00:38:55.960 --> 00:38:59.010
come together to build this
machine, this structure.

00:39:02.580 --> 00:39:10.270
And the crucial insight is
that even our sensations, even

00:39:10.270 --> 00:39:12.940
our emotions, even our
feelings, liberalism

00:39:12.940 --> 00:39:16.080
believes above all
else in our feelings,

00:39:16.080 --> 00:39:20.120
how you feel about politics,
about art, about sexuality,

00:39:20.120 --> 00:39:23.440
this is the holy grail of
liberalism, our feelings.

00:39:23.440 --> 00:39:26.550
But now come the life
sciences and say, feelings?

00:39:26.550 --> 00:39:32.220
Feelings are just biochemical
algorithms calculating what?

00:39:32.220 --> 00:39:35.350
Calculating either
of two things,

00:39:35.350 --> 00:39:39.670
probabilities of survival and
probabilities of reproduction.

00:39:39.670 --> 00:39:41.240
That's it.

00:39:41.240 --> 00:39:44.150
The Homo sapiens, like
giraffes, like elephants, they

00:39:44.150 --> 00:39:47.070
are calculating all the
time, all their body

00:39:47.070 --> 00:39:50.900
is just a calculating machine
for calculating probabilities

00:39:50.900 --> 00:39:53.490
of survival and reproduction.

00:39:53.490 --> 00:39:56.600
This, again, may
sound a bit abstract.

00:39:56.600 --> 00:40:01.050
So I will give two
simple examples.

00:40:01.050 --> 00:40:04.940
First of all,
problems of survival.

00:40:04.940 --> 00:40:06.990
Let's say you are a baboon.

00:40:06.990 --> 00:40:09.800
And you are somewhere in
the Savannah in Africa.

00:40:09.800 --> 00:40:14.790
And you see a tree
with bananas on it.

00:40:14.790 --> 00:40:18.730
And you ask yourself, should
I go and take these bananas?

00:40:18.730 --> 00:40:22.640
But you also see that
there is a lion nearby.

00:40:22.640 --> 00:40:26.910
Now should I or shouldn't
I try and get these bananas

00:40:26.910 --> 00:40:32.220
and risk that while I eat the
bananas the lion will eat me?

00:40:32.220 --> 00:40:36.080
Now in order to reach a
good answer I basically,

00:40:36.080 --> 00:40:39.790
what I need to do, is to
calculate probabilities

00:40:39.790 --> 00:40:43.870
and I need to take into
account a lot of information

00:40:43.870 --> 00:40:46.050
in order to do it correctly.

00:40:46.050 --> 00:40:48.450
I need information
about the bananas.

00:40:48.450 --> 00:40:50.580
How far are they from you?

00:40:50.580 --> 00:40:52.300
Are there any
obstacles in the way?

00:40:52.300 --> 00:40:53.480
How many bananas?

00:40:53.480 --> 00:40:55.800
Are they ripe or are they green?

00:40:55.800 --> 00:40:59.570
It's one thing if there
are 20 ripe bananas

00:40:59.570 --> 00:41:04.080
and it's another thing if there
are just two unripe bananas.

00:41:04.080 --> 00:41:06.600
I also need information
about the lion.

00:41:06.600 --> 00:41:07.490
How far is it?

00:41:07.490 --> 00:41:08.410
How big is it?

00:41:08.410 --> 00:41:09.310
Is it asleep?

00:41:09.310 --> 00:41:10.390
Is it awake?

00:41:10.390 --> 00:41:11.300
Does it seem hungry?

00:41:11.300 --> 00:41:13.080
Does it seem satiated?

00:41:13.080 --> 00:41:17.560
And thirdly, I need a lot
of information about myself.

00:41:17.560 --> 00:41:19.710
How fast can I run?

00:41:19.710 --> 00:41:21.280
How hungry I am?

00:41:21.280 --> 00:41:23.520
If I'm on the verge
of starvation,

00:41:23.520 --> 00:41:28.850
if my energy is so low that
I may die within a few hours

00:41:28.850 --> 00:41:33.520
if I don't eat something, then
no matter how big the danger is

00:41:33.520 --> 00:41:35.660
I should try and
get these bananas

00:41:35.660 --> 00:41:37.780
because otherwise
I'll die anyway.

00:41:37.780 --> 00:41:41.270
If, on the other hand, I
just know I had a big feast,

00:41:41.270 --> 00:41:45.360
there is no reason to risk
my life for these bananas,

00:41:45.360 --> 00:41:49.040
even if the danger
is relatively small.

00:41:49.040 --> 00:41:52.120
Now to reach a good
decision, a good decision

00:41:52.120 --> 00:41:55.100
means a decision that
will enable me to survive,

00:41:55.100 --> 00:41:57.860
I need to take all that
information into account

00:41:57.860 --> 00:42:02.010
and weigh it together somehow,
calculate all the probabilities

00:42:02.010 --> 00:42:03.210
together.

00:42:03.210 --> 00:42:05.560
How do I do it as a baboon?

00:42:05.560 --> 00:42:08.210
I don't take out a
piece of paper and pen,

00:42:08.210 --> 00:42:10.300
or a calculator, or a computer.

00:42:10.300 --> 00:42:11.140
I don't have it.

00:42:11.140 --> 00:42:14.720
And I don't need it
because my entire body

00:42:14.720 --> 00:42:18.330
is a calculator that was
built for millions of years

00:42:18.330 --> 00:42:22.430
by natural selection
to do exactly that.

00:42:22.430 --> 00:42:26.170
What we call emotions,
sensations, feelings,

00:42:26.170 --> 00:42:28.900
are simply
biochemical algorithms

00:42:28.900 --> 00:42:31.850
that take all that information,
all the huge amounts

00:42:31.850 --> 00:42:34.710
of information from
outside and inside,

00:42:34.710 --> 00:42:39.940
and within a split second
reach a certain decision,

00:42:39.940 --> 00:42:41.570
a certain probability.

00:42:41.570 --> 00:42:44.960
Now the result does not
show up as a number,

00:42:44.960 --> 00:42:47.260
like in some futuristic
science fiction

00:42:47.260 --> 00:42:49.240
movie that the
baboon or the person

00:42:49.240 --> 00:42:52.070
sees a number in
front of his eyes, no.

00:42:52.070 --> 00:42:55.230
The result will come
up simply as a feeling.

00:42:55.230 --> 00:42:57.500
This is what feelings are.

00:42:57.500 --> 00:43:01.550
They are the result
of these calculations.

00:43:01.550 --> 00:43:06.250
If the result is that I
should try and get the banana,

00:43:06.250 --> 00:43:10.280
it will come up as the
emotion of courage.

00:43:10.280 --> 00:43:12.050
I will feel very courageous.

00:43:12.050 --> 00:43:16.520
My chest will be puffed up
and I will run to the bananas.

00:43:16.520 --> 00:43:19.370
If the calculations
reach the conclusion,

00:43:19.370 --> 00:43:22.650
reach the result that I
shouldn't risk my life,

00:43:22.650 --> 00:43:26.025
the chances are too small,
then the result again,

00:43:26.025 --> 00:43:26.900
will not be a number.

00:43:26.900 --> 00:43:28.330
It will be a feeling.

00:43:28.330 --> 00:43:31.000
It will be the feeling,
the emotion of fear.

00:43:31.000 --> 00:43:34.000
I will feel very
frightened and run away.

00:43:34.000 --> 00:43:37.980
And sometimes the calculations
are just in the middle.

00:43:37.980 --> 00:43:41.050
It's not clear if it's a good
idea or a bad idea in terms

00:43:41.050 --> 00:43:43.750
of survival to reach
